9\. Implications for NoUI Development

9.1 Calculation Engine Requirements

-   Implement all formula variations by tier exactly as specified

-   Calculate service credit with appropriate precision

-   Determine AMS using correct averaging periods

-   Apply early retirement reductions correctly

-   Handle DRO calculations with marital share methodology

-   Calculate supplemental benefits (IPR, death benefit)

9.2 Transparency Requirements

-   Show every calculation step, not just final result

-   Display formula being applied with variable values

-   Identify which salary months comprise the AMS

-   Explain eligibility determination and any reductions

-   Reference governing document sections for each rule

9.3 Verification Capabilities

-   Enable export of calculation details for audit

-   Support hand-calculation verification workflow

-   Generate test cases from rule definitions

-   Flag calculations that should be manually reviewed

-   Track calculation version when rules change

9.4 Data Quality Requirements

-   Validate salary history completeness before calculation

-   Flag missing or suspicious compensation data

-   Verify service credit records match employment history

-   Confirm tier determination based on hire date

-   Check DRO data completeness for affected members

Conclusion

Benefit calculation is where pension administration demonstrates its
core competency. Every formula, every variable, every rounding decision
must be implemented with precision and documented for verification. The
worked examples in this document establish the calculation methodology
that NoUI must replicate exactly.

The four demo cases provide comprehensive coverage of DERP\'s
calculation scenarios, serving as both documentation and test suite.
When the system produces results matching these calculations to the
penny, with full transparency into every step, it demonstrates the
accuracy and auditability that pension fiduciaries require.

